/*
  This CSS allows the Jetbrains/Intellij Markdown Preview to closely match the appearance of Markdown
  documentation as viewed on GitHub.

  Both the light GitHub theme and the dark theme are included here, although only the light theme works by
  default. The dark theme is deactivated with an as-yet-unsupported "@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)"
  media query. Simply delete and/or comment out the light theme colors below, and then remove the enclosing
  media query from the dark theme colors, in order to use those colors instead.

  Color matching GitHub's syntax coloring inside code fences remains a problem. The Jetbrains preview
  hardcodes the colors of syntactical entities within code fences using explicit style attributes and
  colors derived from your IDE's current theme. Not only do these colors not match GitHub's colors, but
  worse, the IDE's dark theme colors work terribly with GitHub's light theme, and vice versa.

  That's not too big a problem if you want everything light or everything dark at the same time. I, however,
  prefer coding using a dark theme while previewing how my documentation will look using the light theme.

  To that end I'm currently working on a contribution to the Jetbrains public repository so that the IDE's
  preview will provide CSS classes, not just hard-coded colors, for syntactical entities. These are the same
  classes currently used by GitHub: .pl-c, .pl-e, .pl-ent, .pl-k, etc., plus an additional class .pl-x for
  anything syntactically unmatched which should be displayed using the default font color.

  If and when my contribution is accepted, or something similar is added to the Jetbrains environment by
  somebody else, the CSS here is ready to go to render syntax colors matching GitHub colors about as well
  as possible given that Jetbrains's syntax classifications may not completely align with GitHub's.

  If you prefer no syntax coloring at all to the syntax coloring you get, there is commented-out CSS at the
  end of this file that can be uncommented to disable all syntax coloring.

  Copyright Â© 2025 Kerry Shetline <kerry@shetline.com>, MIT license and all of that, derived from CSS
  first created by Sindre Sorhus.
*/

